								<div class="title" id="post-title-1933178">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ihp" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1267048); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1267048&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610202523" alt="Ihp" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1267048)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ihp" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1267048); return false;" >Ihp</a></span> <span class="odate time_1389422487 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">11 Jan 2014 06:41</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1933178">
									

<p>I would like to thank staff for overhauling this guide&#8230; but I can't, because they've taken a half-page guide that didn't need to be overhauled in the first place and put it up to an entire page, two tabs long, and have tried to set precedents that I don't think a lot of people will be very happy with.</p>
<p>Firstly, credit where its due: The staff titles section was a good idea, and is executed well, for the most part (even if we still don't know what HMCL means). If it means that people will have a little more diversity when it comes to calling agents &quot;agents&quot;. However, I highly dislike the fact that it omits &quot;doctor&quot; and replaces it with &quot;researcher&quot;, when the two should be interchangeable; also which takes a less amount of time to write, &quot;Multi-Universal Researcher Bailey&quot; or &quot;Dr. Bailey&quot;?. Secondly, the security clearance expansions themselves, at the top, are also a good idea (the fact that Thaumiel is now a part of site canon makes my heart jump with joy a little). Finally, the bit in the writing guide with the D-Class mentioning they might not be killed is a good idea, even if 99% of the articles featuring them say or imply that there's a monthly termination in some way.</p>
<p>What I don't like is the Class A though C personnel, or Class-E personnel. There is no precedent for the phrase Class-A, Class-B, or Class-C personnel. If people read this guide and see that there's literally not a single thing on the site that mentions them, what are they going to think? I would think &quot;Why would they have it in the guide at all?&quot; I'm not going to use them, that's for sure; if you wanted to establish canon like this and set a precedent, you should have done this when the site was first starting off and not now, almost 6 or 7 years on.</p>
<p>There's also barely any precedent for Class-E, other than the fact that it was in the original guide; exactly one SCP that I can find, <a href="/scp-1337">SCP-1337</a>, uses Class-E personnel. What there is precedent for, however, is Class-E anomalies. From what I can tell, this came from the original Visual Records pages on the wiki had the term &quot;E-###&quot; in the captions, and the term is used by some writers (including myself) to describe SCPs that haven't received classification and/or reports as of yet, and also for lower-scale Anomalous Items in some stories (not the <a href="/log-of-anomalous-items">Log of Anomalous Items</a>, but still.) There's more precedent for E-Class anomalies than there is for E-Class personnel at this point, and they don't even get a nod in any guide at all.</p>
<p>Sadly, the things I dislike in this outweigh the good, so allow me to show my dissatisfaction with a downvote.</p>

							</div>

								
