					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aelanna" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(334454); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=334454&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610202523" alt="Aelanna" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=334454)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aelanna" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(334454); return false;" >Aelanna</a></span> <span class="odate time_1389423682 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">11 Jan 2014 07:01</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1933199">
									

<p>To address this one point, at least, <a href="/mackenzie-glossary">doctor is both a title and a profession and it's often misused</a>. Check the discussion thread there for the long-form explanation from Hornby.</p>
<p>To paraphrase here, though, &quot;Dr.&quot; is a title you're allowed to use if you hold a terminal degree in your field. However, it's not your professional title unless you are in fact a medical doctor, and it's certainly not what be on the nameplate on your office or your ID/business card. This list addresses professional titles, not titles earned from academia.</p>
<p>The correct full title, by the way, would be &quot;Dr. Bailey, Senior Researcher, Extradimensional Research Department&quot; in this case.</p>

							</div>

								
