				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/efs19-mc-kejml" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1381522); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1381522&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610202523" alt="EFS19 - MC_Kejml" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1381522)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/efs19-mc-kejml" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1381522); return false;" >EFS19 - MC_Kejml</a></span> <span class="odate time_1389436704 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">11 Jan 2014 10:38</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1933297">
									

<p>As for the A-E personnel, I always thought the old system was very economical in it's designations: Class D with explicit information who they are and what do they do as the only class to be mentioned, and Class E as the seldom person that came into contact with an uncontained SCPs. Good and simple.<br />
To me, the A-C classes seem excessive and unneeded, only cluttering the already known information about Foundation employees. I am saying this because many of the restrictions about A-C classes overlap or could be overlapped with the current clearances (O5s with As, Site directors with Bs) and so on with little effort. What I see here is unneccessary cluttering of the already established canon, making something that can be simply defined, for example, by rank or headcanon, by too much information (Level 4&#160;B Class Site Director Commander Shepard. Urgh.)</p>
<p>Also, I feel that D-classes somehow got the suspense and horror around them cut out with no real reason. A good example is Protocol 12: A horrible thing that instills fear that the next civilian made into Ds can be literally <span style="text-decoration: underline;">YOU</span>. Now, it's just another kind of prisoner, convict, a person in a refugee camp, hm. The &quot;Other civilian sources&quot; do the old concept little justice, because they hint that there are sources for expendable civilians (say, Sri Lanka slums) and the first time reader would not get as much goosebumps as during the original execution.<br />
Same with the monthly executions. It was some major fleshing out of the Foundation, what does it do in pursuing its goals, and if authors' headcanon said otherwise, the author went and proposed his own interpretation that the executions don't take place without hinting from any other source.<br />
If this is a progress from the old &quot;scary and simple&quot; Foundation to the modern bureucratic Foundation I don't know, but even though the majority of the work on this page and its' following pages is well done, I don't think the steps mentioned above were good steps to take.</p>

							</div>

								
					
