					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/bryx" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1786305); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1786305&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610202523" alt="Bryx" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1786305)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/bryx" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1786305); return false;" >Bryx</a></span> <span class="odate time_1389456417 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">11 Jan 2014 16:06</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1933479">
									

<p>First of all, I'd like to say that this is an extremely impressive document. However, according to a lot of articles, it isn't <em>right</em>. Several standard definitions have been changed, the D-class program has lost quite a bit of punch, and I can't think of any reason to have class A-C, unless it's being appended to the number clearance in which case it's a little late for that. Frankly, seeing it all laid out like this so clear and concise(actually it's much longer), it's like a corset. There's no longer any room to breathe.</p>

							</div>

								
					
